        ii? [Is rust Iron (III) oxide?]
            Hydrated Iron Oxide
    b.
        i.
            Method A prevents iron from rusting by preventing it from being exposed to both oxygen and water. Method A is a barrier method; the paint physically prevents oxygen or water (in the form of e.g. water vapour) from coming into contact with the iron. Since the iron does not contact both of the substances needed for it to rust, it cannot rust.
        ii.
            Galvanisation
        iii.
            Method B prevents iron from rusting even when the zinc coating is scratched because Iron is less reactive than the zinc, so the zinc corrodes instead of the iron. Electrons flow from the zinc to the iron, preventing the formation of iron ions to bond with the oxygen or the water in the air.
4.
    a.
        The student should draw a line in pencil on the chromatography paper near the bottom but not at the bottom so that there is ample room below the line. The student should then put dots of each ink as spaced out from each other as possible on that line. The student should then fill a beaker with solvent, ensuring that the level of solvent does not exceed the amount of space below the line. The student should then put the chromatography paper into the beaker line-end-first, ensuring that the solvent does not directly touch the line or any of the ink-dots. The student should then wait for thirty minutes, or until the dyes have visibly separated, at which point the dyes can be identified as they will have separated from each other.
    b.
        i.
            E must contain a dye which is insoluble in the solvent, since the dot did not move from the start line at all. This must mean that the dot did not dissolve in the solvent, as otherwise it would move to some degree from the start-line.
        ii.
            Inks A and C contain the same dye, because one of its constituent inks (one of the dots vertically above A and C) moved the same distance in A as in C. This implies it is the same dye, since usually only the same dye have the same RF value, which is distance travelled by the dot divided by distance traveled by the solvent front. Since the dots traveled the same distance, it implies they have the same RF value, which implies they are teh same dye. 
        iii.
            The student can use a ruler to measure the distance from the start line of the solvent front and the distance from the start line of the dye in ink C. The student can then divide the distance from the start line of the dye by the distance from the start line of the solvent front, obtaining a value which is less than one.
