8.
    a.
        Because this reaction produces gaseous carbon dioxide, which escapes through the cotton wool, so mass is lost to the atmosphere.
    b.
        Because at the start the concentration of hydrochloric acid is the highest, so there are the most collisions between the HCl in the solution and the marble chips, and this higher rate of collisions leads to a higher rate of reaction. As the reaction goes on, the HCl in the solution is used up, so the concentration drops and there are fewer and fewer collisions between the marble chips and the HCl. This lower rate of collision leads to a lower rate of reaction.
    c.
        This is because the marble chips were in excess; the HCl was used up.
    d.
        i.
            The concentration of the hydrochloric acid
            The size and hence surface area of the marble chips
        ii.
            When the temperature is increased, the average kinetic energy of the HCl particles increases, as kinetic energy is proportional to kelvin temperature. Since the mass of the particles is constant, this implies they move faster. So, there are more frequent collisions (as they are moving faster) between the hydrochloric acid particles and the marble, and these collisions have more energy as the kinetic energy of the particles increased, so the collisions are more likely to surpass the activation energy and lead to a reaction. The increased rate of collisions and increased energy when colliding leads to an increase in the rate of reaction.
